4","1285–1338":"1285–1338","1231–Male":"1231–Deceased","1232–Female":"1232–Deceased","about 1250":"about 1250","1231":"1231","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1263":"1263","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","abt 1258":"about 1258","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1232":"1232","11 September 1297":"11 September 1297","about 1285":"about 1285","Cressingham, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Gressingham, Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Great Cressingham, Norfolk, England":"Great Cressingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cressingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Great or Little Cressingham (Norfolk)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Cressingham was born about 1250, in Great Cressingham, Norfolk, England, his father, William de Cressingham, was 21 and his mother, Emma de Norfolk, was 20. He married Elizabeth of Lancaster in 1283, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 11 September 1297, in Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1250–11 September 1297":"umbes 1250–11. september 1297","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1263–1304":"1263–1304","1285–1338":"1285–1338"